00:09:51,998 --> 00:09:53,299
part of Splinter Cell Conviction.

144
00:09:55,721 --> 00:10:01,205
Well, the first big lesson is that players will work together if they determine that

145
00:10:01,225 --> 00:10:06,229
there's a way for them to use that cooperation to optimize the output of the game's systems.

146
00:10:08,491 --> 00:10:14,555
To talk about that, I'm going to just refer very, very loosely and very broadly to the

147
00:10:14,575 --> 00:10:16,857
detection model that we used in Splinter Cell.

148
00:10:17,879 --> 00:10:19,980
This isn't going to be a technical discussion of this, by the way.

149
00:10:20,420 --> 00:10:22,800
So if you're in the AI business, I apologize.

150
00:10:22,840 --> 00:10:23,480
It's not very deep.

151
00:10:25,041 --> 00:10:29,842
So the number one lesson that we obtained from observing our players is that stealth

152
00:10:29,882 --> 00:10:33,723
is a difficult enough thing to achieve in a single player game, but when you have more

153
00:10:33,763 --> 00:10:37,563
than one player running around in the game space, stealth becomes an extremely fragile

154
00:10:37,603 --> 00:10:37,983
condition.

155
00:10:38,864 --> 00:10:40,544
Okay, well what do I mean by stealth?

156
00:10:40,684 --> 00:10:41,604
What am I talking about?

157
00:10:44,585 --> 00:10:49,988
Stealth for us is really a condition that we achieve by allowing the player to either

158
00:10:50,188 --> 00:10:55,311
be detected by the AI or not be detected by the AI, and it's all the various actions the

159
00:10:55,331 --> 00:10:57,632
player can take one way or the other in that direction.

160
00:10:58,592 --> 00:11:02,214
And to understand how that works, we just need to sort of see that our AI has been kind

161
00:11:02,254 --> 00:11:07,017
of built to be tricked, but also been built to incrementally detect the player.

162
00:11:07,557 --> 00:11:09,158
So there's a number of states that permit this.

163
00:11:09,198 --> 00:11:12,860
We have kind of an idle default state, which is everything that the AI does.

164
00:11:13,907 --> 00:11:17,489
between the time that it's instantiated and the time that it's killed or unloaded,

165
00:11:18,209 --> 00:11:21,271
whether it's systemic or scripted, it's going about its business.

166
00:11:22,231 --> 00:11:25,673
But if something happens to disturb the AI while it's in that state,

167
00:11:26,233 --> 00:11:28,574
then it can move into this kind of perturbed condition

168
00:11:28,614 --> 00:11:32,336
where the behaviors are all about searching for whatever the source of the disturbance was.

169
00:11:33,317 --> 00:11:39,020
And if enough disturbances occur, or if the player just simply outright allows themselves to be detected,

170
00:11:39,360 --> 00:11:41,801
then the AI will enter a state where its behaviors...

171
00:11:42,526 --> 00:11:44,287
are those that we would associate with combat,

172
00:11:44,367 --> 00:11:45,728
with trying to close with the player,

173
00:11:45,768 --> 00:11:46,769
or trying to kill the player,

174
00:11:46,789 --> 00:11:48,570
or more specifically and accurately,

175
00:11:48,630 --> 00:11:50,031
trying to entertain the player

176
00:11:50,291 --> 00:11:51,672
while looking like it's trying to kill them.

177
00:11:55,674 --> 00:11:58,015
And an important point here, again, not technical at all,

178
00:11:58,115 --> 00:12:02,398
is that these transitions that I just described

179
00:12:02,418 --> 00:12:06,020
between states, these are thresholds, basically.

180
00:12:06,040 --> 00:12:07,961
This represents an accumulation of events

181
00:12:08,722 --> 00:12:11,283
that cause the AI to move from one state to another.

182
00:12:12,153 --> 00:12:15,335
And if we look at just even a single player that's operating in the game space, what we

183
00:12:15,375 --> 00:12:20,998
see is that it's actually kind of difficult to know exactly how any one little action

184
00:12:21,038 --> 00:12:24,260
or event contributes to those transitions taking place.

185
00:12:24,280 --> 00:12:24,981
I mean, you can do it.

186
00:12:25,041 --> 00:12:27,062
You can build a giant list or a log.

187
00:12:27,402 --> 00:12:31,564
You can build a big matrix that shows exactly how one particular action by the player under

188
00:12:31,604 --> 00:12:33,546
certain conditions will cause this to take place.

189
00:12:33,566 --> 00:12:35,126
It would just be a lot of work.

190
00:12:37,013 --> 00:12:40,035
If we add a second player to the mix, well, we have to do all that as well.

191
00:12:40,055 --> 00:12:44,296
We have to see how the second player can contribute actions that will cause the second player

192
00:12:44,336 --> 00:12:44,937
to be detected.

193
00:12:45,237 --> 00:12:49,118
But then, very quickly, what we realize is that, actually, it's even worse than that,

194
00:12:49,198 --> 00:12:54,361
because then we have to account for how player one can cause actions that will cause player

195
00:12:54,421 --> 00:12:58,262
two to be detected, and then player two can do things that will cause player one to get

196
00:12:58,282 --> 00:12:58,442
detected.

197
00:12:58,782 --> 00:13:04,325
So you can see, I mean, it turns into a non-linear and highly messy combinatoric.

198
00:13:04,715 --> 00:13:11,741
expression that I wouldn't want to have to draw the matrix for. Bottom line, just because

199
00:13:11,761 --> 00:13:15,804
you have two players in the map doesn't mean you only have twice as much chance of being

200
00:13:15,844 --> 00:13:22,230
detected. In fact, it's possibly a whole lot worse than that. But the flip side is that

201
00:13:22,330 --> 00:13:28,475
if the players are behaving intentionally and they are observing the AI and learning

202
00:13:28,495 --> 00:13:31,798
how the AI operates and learning how the detection model works.

203
00:13:32,451 --> 00:13:37,152
they can actually work together to reduce the chances that they're going to be detected substantially.

204
00:13:39,213 --> 00:13:47,296
And the point is here that players are acting with their knowledge and understanding of the game systems,

205
00:13:48,156 --> 00:13:50,697
not because the game has told them that that's what they should be doing,

206
00:13:51,017 --> 00:13:54,218
but because as they study the game and as they play the game,

207
00:13:54,318 --> 00:13:56,739
whether they're playing cooperatively or not to begin with,

208
00:13:57,319 --> 00:13:59,360
they realize that they have a better chance.

209
00:13:59,974 --> 00:14:02,295
of success if they work together under these conditions.

210
00:14:05,316 --> 00:14:11,699
And what's interesting, maybe even paradoxical, is that that power that comes from that knowledge

211
00:14:11,739 --> 00:14:16,701
and understanding of the game systems, that kind of procedural literacy, actually is giving

212
00:14:16,961 --> 00:14:21,183
the individual players more permission to express themselves as individual players.

213
00:14:22,284 --> 00:14:25,325
And this is something that we actually observed when we were doing our play tests and when

214
00:14:25,365 --> 00:14:26,706
we were looking at other games as well.

215
00:14:27,866 --> 00:14:28,847
Is that self-expression...

216
00:14:29,773 --> 00:14:33,134
becomes a much more interesting and deep and rich thing when there's multiple players around.

217
00:14:33,494 --> 00:14:40,035
At the high level, what we saw was that players working together will do so to develop strategies

218
00:14:41,216 --> 00:14:46,337
in the pursuit of the game's objectives. That at a mid-level, those players will work together

219
00:14:46,597 --> 00:14:52,578
to create planning and to delegate individual low-level tasks in order to support those

220
00:14:52,638 --> 00:14:57,439
plans. And that when they carry out those low-level

221
00:14:57,539 --> 00:14:58,800
actions as individual players.

222
00:14:59,213 --> 00:15:02,774
they're more likely to take risks and to try things that they wouldn't have tried

223
00:15:03,174 --> 00:15:04,795
if they were playing as single-player players.

224
00:15:06,976 --> 00:15:10,037
And that over the course of the entire game, as they are developing this kind of

225
00:15:10,117 --> 00:15:13,218
mastery, this kind of literacy in the game systems, their understanding of

226
00:15:13,419 --> 00:15:17,040
how the AI works, how the 3D navigation system works, all of these things,

227
00:15:17,640 --> 00:15:21,322
that they are willing, more willing than they are in single-player to explore

