00:42:08,429 --> 00:42:11,711
find your own language for it. You can find your own way of doing it. But that's really

609
00:42:11,751 --> 00:42:19,097
the key here. This is what matters. Recognize that when you have more than one player in

610
00:42:19,117 --> 00:42:24,361
the environment, that generates noise. It generates all kinds of noise. It generates

611
00:42:24,421 --> 00:42:31,326
the actual noise of multiple players' characters moving around in the game space. So the sensory

612
00:42:31,366 --> 00:42:33,427
noise. It generates a system's noise.

613
00:42:34,126 --> 00:42:37,467
of multiple players perturbing the system, the AI, and all these other things in lots

614
00:42:37,508 --> 00:42:42,410
of different ways that make the environment more chaotic. And you have the social noise

615
00:42:42,470 --> 00:42:46,391
of these two people who might be sitting on a couch or might be talking over their microphones

616
00:42:47,372 --> 00:42:53,395
distracting each other. So when you're designing the ingredients at the level of kind of aesthetic

617
00:42:53,435 --> 00:42:59,377
level of level design, focus on readability, on the legibility of those ingredients first,

618
00:42:59,918 --> 00:43:03,279
then make it pretty. To give you a good example of this.

619
00:43:03,860 --> 00:43:10,422
on conviction in the single-player maps, which were beautiful. Lighting was initially done

620
00:43:10,462 --> 00:43:16,203
as a kind of an art pass. Basically, the lighting fit the logic, the architecture, the intentions,

621
00:43:16,263 --> 00:43:21,865
the mood of those maps, and it was beautiful. And once it was beautiful, then after multiple

622
00:43:21,905 --> 00:43:25,746
iterations, looking at heat map results, all this other stuff, the team was able to go

623
00:43:25,866 --> 00:43:30,888
in and tweak and adjust the lighting to work well with the AI's detection model. In the

624
00:43:30,908 --> 00:43:31,628
case of co-op...

625
00:43:32,065 --> 00:43:34,646
we had to do it 180 degrees in the opposite direction.

626
00:43:35,826 --> 00:43:39,067
We built, our lighting was giant circles of light,

627
00:43:39,147 --> 00:43:40,747
like you'd see in a Bugs Bunny cartoon.

628
00:43:41,447 --> 00:43:43,088
And we would sort of string these circles of light

629
00:43:43,108 --> 00:43:44,148
to create our shadow paths.

630
00:43:44,168 --> 00:43:47,069
And once we knew that we had enough of a shadow path

631
00:43:47,109 --> 00:43:48,409
to accommodate more than one player,

632
00:43:49,309 --> 00:43:51,570
then we'd do a pass to try to substitute

633
00:43:51,610 --> 00:43:52,650
those light sources with something

634
00:43:52,670 --> 00:43:54,010
maybe it felt a little more logical.

635
00:43:55,010 --> 00:43:56,851
And then we would go through and do these iterative passes

636
00:43:56,891 --> 00:43:58,311
to make it more discreet and more subtle,

637
00:43:58,891 --> 00:44:00,032
and have it look a little bit nicer.

638
00:44:01,150 --> 00:44:03,332
And the message there is, players will forgive that.

